Rating: 4
I loved this! Felt as though I were in Italy while eating it. I changed it a lot. Used regular pork chops, but dusted them with flour, salt & pepper before pan frying them. Used fresh basil instead of thyme and squeezed fresh lemon juice over the dish at the end. It was very light, fresh and so yummy. I will make this often. Very easy!

Rating: 3
a simple and delicious dinner! I used regular porkchops, and garbanzo beans instead of white beans...I also mashed up some green olives in lieu of green olive paste. Even with all the substitutions, this recipe was a hit!

Rating: 4
This was a great recipe that complimented smoked pork chops perfectly! I added a little white wine to the tomatoes and garlic before adding the beans. I did not have any green olive paste but made my own with brined olives in the blender with a touch of olive oil. I even added a few olives at the end as garnish. The olive flavour with the tomatoes and thyme brought out the smoky sweetness of the chops and made a perfect and simple meal! This one surprised me!

Rating: 4
I made this last night and we really liked it. I overcooked the beans and tomatoes a bit, so it was kind of mushy but it had a really great flavor. I used a Kalamata Olive tapenade, instead of the green olive paste. I think I might try to make this without adding it to porkchops next time and try it as a side-dish.

Rating: 3
Instead of using smoked pork chops, I prepared the pork as in Garlic-Rosemary pork chops (http://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/Rosemary-Pork-Chops-240946) and made the beans according to the directions. Served with a winter greens salad. Super easy, fast and delicious!

